FORECAST: The ol’ 1-2. Pick the first and second horses home, in the right order. If any of your selections are non-runners your bet will be void.

31589879.1200.comment: It's hard to look beyond BRESSON, who just lost out to a highly promising Godolphin colt at Newmarket last month, form which was boosted when the winner recently went close in Group 2 company. The Dubawi colt remains open to improvement and represents the yard responsible for the winners of this in 2019 and 2020, and one of the divisions last year. Tarjeeh shaped with plenty of encouragement at Windsor and is next on the list ahead of likely-looking newcomer Lenormand.

runners.name: Beauld As Brass
runners.comment: Foaled March 11. 2,000 gns yearling, Brazen Beau gelding. Half-brother to 2-y-o 6f winner Attila Rex. Dam 11.5f-1¾m winner who stayed 2m out of 1m-1¼m winner Bonne Etoile. Probably best watched on debut.

runners.name: Bresson
runners.comment: Shaped well when third on debut over 6.5f here in May, and again when just touched off by Victory Dance (close second in Group 2 company since) upped to 7f at Newmarket (good). Sets a good standard for the others to aim at.

runners.name: Captain Cuddles (IRE)
runners.comment: Wasn't beaten far when fifth in a 10-runner Sandown novice (7f, good) on debut a fortnight ago. Perhaps lacks the long-term scope of several of these, but live each-way chance if able to build on that effort here. Yard also saddles Classic.

runners.name: Classic
runners.comment: Foaled March 31. 260,000 gns yearling. Half-brother to smart winner up to 1¼m Beautiful Morning and useful 1¼m winner La Gloire. Dam 2-y-o 7f winner who stayed 11.5f. Well worth a second look in the betting, albeit Captain Cuddles is presumably the stable No 1.

runners.name: Dancing Magic (IRE)
runners.comment: Displayed plenty of ability first time out when fourth of 10 at Salisbury (7f, good to firm) last month, beaten around a length. On that evidence there are certainly races to be won with this colt, but it's over middle distances next year that he's likely to really flourish.

runners.name: Dawn Vega
runners.comment: Foaled February 14. 160,000 gns yearling, Lope De Vega colt. Half-brother to 2-y-o 9.5f winner Ebony and 2-y-o 7f winner Encipher, both useful. Yard's newcomers typically come on for a run, but a peak in the betting is advised all the same.

runners.name: Dream Of Mischief
runners.comment: From a family his yard knows well and there were positives to take from his recent debut here (6f, good), finishing in mid-field but he wasn't knocked about and is sure to improve for the experience and this step up in trip.

runners.name: Forest Demon (IRE)
runners.comment: Beat just one rival home on his introduction in a 10-runner Salisbury maiden, finishing almost seven lengths adrift of the re-opposing Dancing Magic. Clearly has work to do if he's to make an impact here.

runners.name: Frequent Flyer (IRE)
runners.comment: Foaled February 10. €80,000 yearling. Dam, 8.4f-11f winner, half-sister to smart 2-y-o 6f/7f winner Masekela out of useful 10.5f-1½m winner Lady's Purse. Top yard can ready a newcomer and interesting to see what the market has to say.

runners.name: Lenormand
runners.comment: Foaled February 21. 600,000 gns half-brother to smart winner up to 1¼m and Best of Days and 1¼m winner Birdcage Walk. Dam 1m-11f winner. Represents powerful connections and confidence behind him in the betting would look significant.

runners.name: Redcliff Glen (GER)
runners.comment: Foaled April 23. 75,000 gns yearling. Dam, 1¼m winner who stayed 1½m, closely related to smart 2-y-o 7f winner Lucky Chappy out of useful 2-y-o 7f winner Germane. Certainly not devoid of appeal on paper, but is starting out in what looks a pretty warm contest.

runners.name: Seattle Time
runners.comment: Half-brother to 3 winners, including smart winner up to 7f Great Ambassador and useful 1m winner Seattle Rock. Kept on into fifth on debut at Salisbury (hot on the heels of fourth-placed Dancing Magic) and place possibilities here with improvement on the cards.

runners.name: Tarjeeh (IRE)
runners.comment: Good pedigree and shaped well under considerate handling when fourth of nine in a 6f Windsor maiden last month, doing all his best work at the finish. Extra furlong here will be a big help and likely to be winning races before long.

runners.name: Wholetthedogsout (IRE)
runners.comment: Little impact in maidens at Lingfield and Salisbury (behind Dancing Magic and Seattle Time at the latter course) and it's hard to envisage her playing a leading role.

31589879.1200.verdict: The Gosden yard has a striking record in this race in recent years and they have another strong contender in BRESSON, who was only just caught over 7f at Newmarket last time and sets a good standard on that form. Several of the others have also shown clear promise and the pick of that bunch could be Tarjeeh, who made some eyecatching late headway at Windsor and looks a likely improver upped in trip on his second start. There are also plenty of newcomers who need a close look, notably Godolphin's 600,000gns colt Lenormand.[David Moon]

runners.spotlight: Time Test half-brother to three winners; ran into trouble at Salisbury (7f, good to firm) on his debut last month but he kept on well and was beaten less than 2l; ties in closely with Dancing Magic on that form and he could be dangerous on his second start.

Didn't really live up to market expectations at Windsor (6f, good to firm; 100-30) on debut but he made some promising late headway into fourth behind an impressive winner; should be more streetwise this time and he's a likely improver on this step up in trip.

80,000euros yearling; first foal; dam 8.4f-1m3f winner (RPR 87), sister to Group-placed 1m2f winner Asoof, half-sister to 7f 2yo Listed winner/Oaks fourth Masakela out of French 1m4f Group 3 winner; yard 16% with 2yos here in recent years and he needs watching in market.

Well-bred colt, by Dubawi out of Group 3 winner Shutter Speed; made promising start with his third here (6.5f, good to soft) in May and he built on that when going very close under a positive ride at Newmarket (7f, good) last month; sets good standard on that form and he's open to further progress; yard won this in 2019 and 2020 and also landed a division last year.

75,000gns yearling; second foal; dam 1m2f AW winner (RPR 74), closely related to Italian 7.5f 2yo Listed winner Lucky Chappy, half-sister to Listed-placed 1m winner Granted; in-form yard has 18% record with 2yos this year; interesting to see how he figures in the market.

600,000gns foal; fifth foal; half-brother to 7f-1m2f winner Best Of Days (including 2yo Group 2/Australian Group 1; RPR 110) and 1m2f winner Birdcage Walk (87); dam German 1m Listed/GB 10.8f winner (99), half-sister to 1m2f Group 3 winner Azmeel; very interesting newcomer and he needs a close look.

160,000gns half-brother to winners Ebony (French 9.5f AW 2yo; RPR 102) and Encipher (7f 2yo; 100); dam French 1m1f/1m2f winner, half-sister to triple 1m Group 1 winner Ervedya; plenty to like on paper and he needs checking in market with Hollie Doyle booked on debut.

95,000gns Kodiac colt; 22-1 at Sandown (7f, good) two weeks ago but he gave it a good shot from the front before finishing a 3l fifth of ten; that form is not far off the standard here and he's open to improvement on his second start; in the mix.

Brother to 1m-1m6f winner Dancing Harry (including 2yo); 6-1 at Salisbury (7f, good to firm) last month and he didn't get much luck before finishing a close fourth of ten; that was a promising start and he should know more this time; respected.
Finished in rear at big prices in two 7f maidens at Lingfield (good) and Salisbury (good to firm); remains best watched for now.

2,000gns yearling; fifth foal; half-brother to Italian 6f 2yo winner Attila Rex; dam 11.4f/1m6f winner (RPR 70), half-sister to 7f-1m2f winner Soviet Secret and 5f-8.6f winner Handsome Falcon; this looks a tough starting point and he's best watched.

260,000gns half-brother to winners Beautiful Morning (7f-1m2f including 2yo/Group 3; RPR 106) and La Gloire (1m2f; 85); dam Listed-placed 7f 2yo winner (94), half-sister to 10.5f Group 3 winner Ombre Legere; holds a Derby entry and he needs a close look on debut; stablemate of Captain Cuddles.
Half-brother to a Group 3 winner but he made a low-key start at Salisbury (7f, good to firm; 12-1) last month and was behind two of today's rivals in that race; best watched.

Oasis Dream half-brother to connections' progressive 1m-1m1f handicapper Rebel Territory; shaped with some promise when 40-1 here last month (6f, good) but he has quite a bit to find on this step up in trip and could be one for a bit further down the line.

148049.terms:
Paddy Power offer Best Odds Guaranteed on all UK & Irish Horse Racing from 8am on the day of the race. So, if you take a price on a horse and the Starting Price (SP) is bigger we will pay you out at the bigger odds!

For Example:
* If you take a price of 3/1 and the selection wins with an SP of 4/1, we pay you 4/1.
* If you take a price of 3/1 and the selection wins with an SP of 2/1, we STILL pay you 3/1. 
* So you get the best of both worlds!

* Best Odds Guaranteed applies to Singles & Multiples on win & each way markets only.

Best Odds Guaranteed does not apply to:
* Bets placed at ante-post odds
* Betting-in-running bets
* Combined horse bets
* Bets on international racing
* Customers whose registered address is outside the UK or Ireland
* Power Price selections
* Bets placed before 8am on the day of the race
* Bets placed with a Power Up token



 
The maximum payment to any one client in respect of our Best Odds Guaranteed concession is £1,000 per day.

For commercial reasons, Paddy Power reserves the right to exclude selected customers from receiving various promotions including Best Odds Guaranteed.
